Chapter-4-Question-1-Answer.content:
Answer to question from here.
Below, I have presented 2 answers. One uses dictionaries, while the other does not. Have a look!
name = input(&quot;Enter the name of the Student: &quot;) 
subject = input(&quot;Enter the Subject Name: &quot;) 

table = { 
	&quot;Alice&quot; : { 
		&quot;Biology&quot; : 92, 
		&quot;Chemistry&quot; : 70, 
		&quot;English&quot; : 88, 
	}, 
	&quot;Bob&quot; : { 
		&quot;Biology&quot; : 95, 
		&quot;Chemistry&quot; : 80, 
		&quot;English&quot; : 79, 
	}, 
	&quot;Charlie&quot; : { 
		&quot;Biology&quot; : 89, 
		&quot;Chemistry&quot; : 75, 
		&quot;English&quot; : 77, 
	}
}

if (name in table) and (subject in table[name]): 
	print(table[name][subject]) 
else: 
	print(&quot;Can&#039;t find student or score&quot;) 
Explanation
The lines
name = input(&quot;Enter the name of the Student: &quot;) 
subject = input(&quot;Enter the Subject Name: &quot;) 
Simply ask the user for the name of the student, and the name of the subject, and store these in the variables name and subject
The line

table = { 
	&quot;Alice&quot; : { 
		&quot;Biology&quot; : 92, 
		&quot;Chemistry&quot; : 70, 
		&quot;English&quot; : 88, 
	}
	&quot;Bob&quot; : { 
		&quot;Biology&quot; : 95, 
		&quot;Chemistry&quot; : 80, 
		&quot;English&quot; : 79, 
	}
	&quot;Charlie&quot; : { 
		&quot;Biology&quot; : 89, 
		&quot;Chemistry&quot; : 75, 
		&quot;English&quot; : 77, 
	}
}

Defines a nested dictionary, a dictionary that contains other dictionaries.
The ‘outter’ dictionary has the student name as the key and for the value it has another dictionary. These sub-dictionaries have the subject as the key and the score as the value. This means, you can do something like this:
if (name in table) and (subject in table[name]): 
	print(table[name][subject]) 
else: 
	print(&quot;Can&#039;t find student or score&quot;) 
Where, the evaluation for name=“Alice” and subject = “Biology” is as follows:
table[name][subject] 
→ table[&quot;Alice&quot;][&quot;Biology&quot;] 
→ { &quot;Biology&quot; : 92, &quot;Chemistry&quot; : 70, &quot;English&quot; : 88, }[&quot;Biology&quot;] 
→ 92 
name in table 
evaluates as below:
name in table 
→ &quot;Alice&quot; in {&quot;Alice&quot; : {...}, &quot;Bob&quot; : {...}, &quot;Charlie&quot; : {...}} 

Here’s a solution without using dictionaries:
name = input(&quot;Name: &quot;)
subject = input(&quot;Subject: &quot;)

if name == &quot;Alice&quot;:
    if subject == &quot;Biology&quot;:
        print(92)
    elif subject == &quot;Chemistry&quot;:
        print(70)
    elif subject == &quot;English&quot;:
        print(88)
    else:
        print(&quot;Subject not found.&quot;)

elif name == &quot;Bob&quot;:
    if subject == &quot;Biology&quot;:
        print(95)
    elif subject == &quot;Chemistry&quot;:
        print(80)
    elif subject == &quot;English&quot;:
        print(79)
    else:
        print(&quot;Subject not found.&quot;)

elif name == &quot;Charlie&quot;:
    if subject == &quot;Biology&quot;:
        print(89)
    elif subject == &quot;Chemistry&quot;:
        print(75)
    elif subject == &quot;English&quot;:
        print(77)
    else:
        print(&quot;Subject not found.&quot;)

else:
    print(&quot;Name not found.&quot;)

Not only does using dictionaries make this easier to write, but you can add students and subjects and change scores without having to rewrite long scripts!
